long_desc.thetext:
Here's the code:

      var item = this.__array.pop();
      this.__updateLength();
      // ...      
      this.fireDataEvent("changeBubble", {
        value: [],
        name: this.length + "",
        old: [item],
        item: this
      });
      this.fireDataEvent("change",
        {
          start: this.length - 1,
          end: this.length - 1,
          type: "remove",
          removed : [item],
          added : []
        }, null
      );

``start`` is erroneously decremented, because ``this.length`` is already the length of popped array. See example with ``remove`` equivalent. The test for the pop change event asserts the same wrong values. 

There're also other minor issues with ``end``. Like in http://tinyurl.com/ltwg8gz, where it's neither the end index, nor the length of deleted items. It's minor because ``start`` is usually correct, and with ``added`` and ``removed`` a change is determined.

Also, as a related consideration, there's ``a.splice(-1, 1)`` which fires ``start`` as is, -1. In some "interop" cases this can be undesired, so normalizing can be a good idea.
